CHAPTER 3

LINUX BASICS AND SYSTEM STARTUP
* Identify Lİnux filesystem
* Identify differences: partitions vs filesystems
* describe the boot process
* Install linux on a computer


BIOS : The first step
 power on ------> BIOS (Basic input/ output system)-------------> initializes(başlatmak) the screen and keyboard and tests the main memory

power on ----> BIOS ----->Master Boot Record(MBR) also known as first Sector of the hard disk----> Boot loader (e.g.GRUB)---> Kernel(Linux OS)---> Initial RAM disk-initramfs( çekirdeğe gömülü ve önyükleme sürecinin erken bir aşamasında yüklenen bir kök dosya sistemidir) image-----> /sbin/init(parent process)


a- Master Boot Record (MBR) and Boot Loader

MBR
-> Partition(bölme)1 (Bootable-çalıştırılabilir)
    searches for GRUB and loads it into RAM

-> Partition 2

-> Partition 3


initramfs ---> programs and binary files
                  * mount proper root filesystem
                  * providing kernel functionally
                  * locating devices
                  *  locating drivers and load them  
                  * checking for errors in root filesystem







Filesystems supported by Linux
-> Conventional disk filesystems(ext3, ext4, xfs, Btrfs, JFS, NTFS; vfat, etc
-> Flash storage filesystems(ubifs, iffs2, yaffs, etc)
-> Database filesystems
-> Special purpose(amaç) filesystems(profcs, sysfs, tmpfs, squashfs, debugfs, etc)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Root directory of the entire file systems hierarchy
/bin/ --> essential user command binaries
/boot/ --> static files of the boot loader
/dev/ --> device files
/etc/ --> host-specific sysem configuration
/home/ --> user home directories
/lib/ --> essential(temel) shared(ortak) libraries and kernel modules
/media/ --> mount point for removable(çıkarılabilir) media
/mnt/ -->mount point for a temporarily(geçici olarak) mounted filesystems
/opt/ --> add on application software packages
/sbin/ --> system binaries
/srv/ --> data for services provided by this system
/tmp/ --> temporary files
/usr/ --> (multi)-user utilities and applications 
/var/ --> variable files
/root/ --> home directory for the root user
/proc/ --> virtual filesystem documenting kernel and process status as text files

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Partitions in the Lİnux HArd Disk

  Linux Hard Disk(sda)
    * /(sda1)
    * home(sda2)
    * var (sda3)
    * swap(sda4)








  
